<br>
I vaguely remember reading that the various new owners all experienced assorted problems with the ship. She changed hands, each time due to some problem.<br>
<br>
One new owner changed her name from Mary Celeste to &quot;Amazon&quot; (I think it was), even though rechristening a ship was considered bad luck by many seafarers. The captain died or went mad, and after changing hands a few more times, she was re-rechristened Mary Celeste again.<br>
<br>
Quite a few of the seamen involved with the Mary Celeste after she was found abandoned the first time met strange deaths, committed suicide, went mad, or were accused of odd crimes they swore they did not commit.<br>
<br>
Another strange case of an odd ship is the Baychimo. A 20th century ship, the Baychimo did not like having a crew aboard. She'd run aground or terrify the crew away, then drift off. She'd be found, boarded, and searched, sometimes drifting away with the terrified people on board wondering what was going on. She always eventually let them off somewhere, and would take off to sea again. The Baychimo was well known to mysteriously &quot;run aground&quot; only to be free again with no warning. Apparently, the Baychimo loved the sea, for she was spotted all over, from polar ice (where she was boarded a few times) to the equatorial regions, where puzzled seamen recognized her from stories. The book that had her story was written in the 1970's, and the author claimed that at the time of the writing, she had last been seen (confirmed, he claimed) in 1966. She was said to be slow and lumbering when she wanted to be seen, allowing herself to be boarded, and also to be speedy and able to outrace the wind. Strange.<br>
<br>
Karuna<br>
<br>
